'''Jean Soupert''' (1834–1906) was a [[Luxembourg]]-born [[floriculturist]], who specialized in [[plant breeding|breeding]] rose [[cultivar]]s.
== Biography == In 1855, with a friend, [[Pierre Notting]], he established the "Soupert & Notting" company specializing in growing roses in [[Limpertsberg]]. In 1857, Soupert married Anne Marie Notting, [[Pierre Notting]]’s sister. During the next years, and as from 1861, “Soupert & Notting” obtained medals at international competitions in [[France]], [[Belgium]], [[Germany]], the [[Netherlands]], the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[United States of America]].
In 1874, [[Jean Pernet, père]] from [[Lyon, France|Lyon]] dedicated them a moss rose: “Soupert & Notting”. Jean Soupert died in Luxembourg in 1906.
==Legacy== After his death, his three sons, Jean-Pierre, Pierre-Alphonse and Jean-Constant Soupert took over the rosarium.<ref>[http://www.luxembourg.co.uk/rose_research.doc The luxembourgish rose patrimony/the roses of Soupert & Notting]</ref>
